Weeeell, I can't shake my discomfort with the idea that yes, this may
be reasonable for her parents, yet would it be different if the girl
were a ward of the state? (There's a long history -- not always a nice
history -- of individuals with severe disabilities who were lifetime
residents of state schools (or institutions) who also received some
operations that in effect made it easier for the state, although the
operations were entirely optional. I'm thinking of sterilization, and
of wide-scale tooth extraction (e.g., for individuals who were
determined to require tube-feeding for the rest of their life).

For me, there's something slippery and generally uncomfortable with it,
especially if this became more widely-accepted (e.g., lifting patients
is one of the primary causes of workers' comp claims at some state
facilities -- would it make sense to restrict the patients' growth
instead?).

