I read the parents' blog, as well as most of the comments in their
guestbook, and to be quite honest, I think what they did was fine.

Many comments centered on "it's not in the child's best interests,
rather it was for their own convenience".  Part of what made it sticky
is that it does BOTH.

Yes, it does make it easier to lift their daughter.  It is easier for
them to manage her weight when bathing her, feeding her, changing her
diapers.  So yes, it DOES make their life easier. But what the
naysayers based on that reason don't realize is that BECAUSE it makes
their life easier, it also results in a huge improvement in the quality
of their daughter's life.

Because they can relatively easily manage her weight, they can and will
move her more often, thus preventing bedsores.  Because she's little,
than can carry her from room to room, and keep her a part of their
life, thus combating boredome on her part (She has the mind of a
3-month old, and 3-month olds *do* need stimulation and exposure to new
things, or they too get bored).  And moving her around, helps the
bedsore issue as well.

Because she is small, they will better be able to keep her clean - and
I'm sure everyone agrees that hygiene is important.  She will have
fewer health problems.

And because she is small, they will be able to keep her at home until
they are too old to care for her - potentially the next 40 years, or
even more.  Once she got too big for them to handle, they likely would
have had to put her in an institution, which are not known for the best
care.  Patients like her, at full size rarely get immersion baths -
rather they are most often sponge-bathed.   And the folks in
institutions have a caregiver to patient ratio MUCH worse than this
little girl will have.

There were also a lot of folks who protested with "would you like it if
someone else made the decision to mutilate *you*??"  And I think that
arguement is just plain silly.  The girl has a mind of a 3-month old.
She is not capable of understanding or even caring.   And she never
will.  Projecting your own horror at a decision being taking out of
your own hands isn't useful.  Making no decision on your child's behalf
is the same as making a decision in the other way.

She doesn't have the capability to understand that while she might be
uncomfortable for a few days now, it might save her years of discomfort
later, when she gets bedsores, isn't moved the necessary 20 times per
day, and is only given occasional spongebaths.   When she is 5' 6"
tall, and weighs 220 pounds (patients with her condition tend toward
obesity) no one will cuddle her on their lap.  Ever.

Cathy Weeks
