I think what made me most uncomfortable about the whole thing was that they
kept on insisting that 'The "Ashley Treatment" is intended to improve our
daughter's quality of life and not to convenience her caregivers.'  As you
say, it is quite obvious that it does both; the parents are not being entirely
honest with themselves or the public.  When combined with the  complete
absence of self-doubt, it's just weird to read.  I would have been far happier
to read, 'Yeah, it will help us look after her, and we really had to think
carefully about the basis of our decision-making,' but they don't say that --
in fact, they say the opposite.

The other issue is the hormone treatment itself.  The only hormone treatment I
know about from the '60s is the David Reimer case -- not quite the same thing,
nor a happy ending.  However it certainly indicates the strength of the
God-complex that some Drs in the '60s suffered from.  It sounds very likely to
me that some poor girls then *were* given hormone treatment to make them
shorter -- but as they would only be in their 40s now the experiments done on
them can hardly be said to be complete, and the treatment has "somehow" fallen
out of fashion.  Who knows what will happen to them post-menopause?  Have they
been followed up at all?  Therefore the oestrogen treatment given to this
disabled girl might not be as uncomplicated a matter as the parents believe.
I hope it is.  I'm just surprised that the specialists claimed to *know*.

I agree very much with one statement in the replies, and it's true for
probably all Western countries, at least:

What has brought us to the place as a society where this debate even has to
happen?

It's a long history... a history of hiding people with disabilities and clumping
them into institutions.  We have a lot to be embarrassed about - if you're
willing to see it.  Families do have much more support to keep their children
at home - but we're no where near to where we need to be.  It's not only the
physical care of children who grow; it's the lack of supports in the adult
system that create a fear of appropriate care outside of the home.
&lt;snip&gt;
What are the alternatives for this family?  Perhaps if we created a system
where families felt they had some control?  What if we provided appropriate
supports in the home and community that met their needs?  That is different
then underpaid workers who come and go... it is about establishing a much
deserved level of respect for caregivers - pay/benefits.  That is about us as
a society.

(From Message 56)

