And, realistically, if you're going to do a hysterectomy, you might as well
do the appendectomy too, and avoid possible future surgery, since there is
no real need for an appendix.

I also have a friend who has a history of very, very invasive ovarian cancer
in her family, and at the recommendation of her doctors and the cancer
specialists, after having her second child (by C-section), had a complete
hysterectomy as well. It seemed drastic in someone in her early 30's, but
the cancer had killed her mother when her mother was only in her late 40's,
and she was done having children. She felt early menopause was a small price
to pay to avoid the cancer risk, and that since she was stuck with a
C-section anyway, she might as well get the surgery all done at once and
only have one recovery to deal with instead of two.

